data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code uses the **timeout enforcement** pattern — aborting a thread that exceeds a time limit. Here's the inventory:

| API Found | Line | Purpose |
|-----------|------|---------|
| `thread.Abort()` | after `Join` | Kill thread on timeout |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | inner try | Catch the injected exception |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | inner catch | Suppress the abort to continue |

All three APIs throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` or are no-ops in .NET 6+.

---

## Migrated Code (Task-based with CancellationToken)

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerException is OperationCanceledException
                                             && cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### What changed and why

| Old (.NET Framework) | New (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` | `Task.Run(...)` | Task-based model integrates with `CancellationToken`; avoids manual thread management |
| `thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` | Token auto-cancels after the timeout — cooperative, not preemptive |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | `OperationCanceledException` is the standard cancellation signal |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *(removed)* | No abort to reset; cooperative cancellation doesn't inject exceptions |
| `Func<T> work` | `Func<CancellationToken, T> work` | Work must receive the token to cooperate with cancellation |

### Callers must update too

```csharp
// OLD — work ignores cancellation (won't stop on its own)
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => ComputeResult(), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// NEW — work checks the token at regular intervals
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();   // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return BuildResult();
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

---

## Critical Pitfalls

**1. Cancellation is cooperative — it won't interrupt uncooperative code.**
Unlike `Thread.Abort`, which forcibly injects an exception at any point, `CancellationToken` only works at explicit checkpoints. If `work` calls a long-running synchronous method that never checks the token, the timeout won't fire until that call returns. Insert `ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` between expensive operations.

**2. `Thread.Sleep` doesn't respond to cancellation.**
Replace `Thread.Sleep(ms)` inside your work with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or `await Task.Delay(ms, token)` so the sleep is interrupted on cancellation.

**3. Dispose `CancellationTokenSource` — it leaks timers.**
The `using` statement in the migrated code handles this. The original had no equivalent concern.

**4. Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException` inside the work delegate.**
The old `catch (ThreadAbortException) { Thread.ResetAbort(); }` block silently swallowed the abort. If you replicate this by catching and swallowing `OperationCanceledException` inside the work, the timeout mechanism breaks entirely — the task will appear to succeed.

**5. Truly uncooperative code (native calls, third-party libs) can't be cancelled this way.**
If your `work` delegate calls code you can't modify to accept a token, the only reliable replacement for `Thread.Abort` is to move that work to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()` on timeout.

---

## Optional: Async version (preferred for new code)

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work,
        TimeSpan timeout,
        CancellationToken externalToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        // If externalToken was cancelled, OperationCanceledException propagates as-is
    }
}
```

This version links an external caller token with the timeout, so the work stops on whichever fires first — and the caller can distinguish timeout from external cancellation.
